statement.p:
For a differentiable map
T(u,v)=(x(u,v),y(u,v)),
the Jacobian determinant is
\boxed{ J_T(u,v) = \frac{\partial(x,y)}{\partial(u,v)} = \det \begin{pmatrix} x_u \amp x_v\\ y_u \amp y_v \end{pmatrix} = x_u y_v-x_v y_u. }
The ordinary local area scale factor is
\boxed{ |J_T(u,v)|. }

subsection.p:
Let R be the wedge 1\le x\le3,\qquad 0\le y\le2x. Compute \iint_R (x+y)\,dA. Use x=u,\qquad y=uv, with 1\le u\le3,\qquad 0\le v\le2. The Jacobian determinant is J_T(u,v)=u. Also, x+y=u+uv=u(1+v). Therefore
\iint_R (x+y)\,dA \amp= \int_1^3\int_0^2 u(1+v)\,u\,dv\,du \amp= \int_1^3 u^2 \left[\int_0^2(1+v)\,dv\right]du \amp= \int_1^3 u^2 \left[v+\frac{v^2}{2}\right]_0^2du \amp= \int_1^3 4u^2\,du \amp= 4\left[\frac{u^3}{3}\right]_1^3 \amp= \frac{104}{3}.
So \boxed{ \iint_R (x+y)\,dA=\frac{104}{3}. }

In differential form language, the signed area element changes by
\boxed{ dx\wedge dy = J_T(u,v)\,du\wedge dv. }
For ordinary area integrals, we use the absolute value:
\boxed{ dA=|J_T(u,v)|\,du\,dv. }

statement.p:
In polar coordinates, x^2+y^2=r^2, so q=12-r^2. The disk is 0\le r\le2,\qquad 0\le\theta\le2\pi. Therefore
Q \amp= \iint_R (12-x^2-y^2)\,dA \amp= \int_0^{2\pi}\int_0^2 (12-r^2)\,r\,dr\,d\theta \amp= 2\pi\int_0^2(12r-r^3)\,dr \amp= 2\pi \left[ 6r^2-\frac{r^4}{4} \right]_0^2 \amp= 2\pi(24-4) \amp= 40\pi.
So \boxed{ Q=40\pi. }
